                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 812.63/42.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to Vice
                        Consul <persName type="to">Guyant</persName>
                    </hi>.</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>, <lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1915-03-03">
                            <hi rend="italic">March 3, 1915</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: The Department has received your despatch No. 328
                    of February 8, 1915, reporting [etc.]</p>
                <p>You will inform the Department as to the method employed by the authorities in
                    giving notice of the nullification of mining titles and if such notice was given
                    by means of a decree you will forward a copy of such decree.</p>
                <p>You will inform the appropriate authorities that the United States Government
                    expects that American owners of mining titles in your district, who acquired
                    their titles in good faith and in conformity with Mexican law, shall not be
                    deprived of such titles except upon terms of equitable compensation and by due
                    process of law.</p>
                <p>I am [etc.]</p>
                <closer>For the Secretary of State: <lb/>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Wilbur J. Carr.</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
